      "key_concept": {
        "definition": "Three main theoretical derivations of the gravity model:<br><br>1. Anderson (1979) — Armington assumption: Goods are differentiated by country of origin. Each country produces a unique good. Consumers have CES preferences. Trade costs are iceberg (a fraction of goods melts in transit). Solving the model yields: $X_{ij} = \\frac{Y_i Y_j}{Y^W} \\left(\\frac{t_{ij}}{\\Pi_i P_j}\\right)^{1-\\sigma}$, where $t_{ij}$ is trade cost, $\\Pi_i$ and $P_j$ are multilateral resistance terms (price indices). This is the theoretical gravity equation.<br><br>2. Helpman and Krugman (1985) — Monopolistic competition: Each firm produces a differentiated product under increasing returns. Consumers love variety. Trade costs are iceberg. The gravity equation emerges from the model: $X_{ij} = \\frac{Y_i Y_j}{Y^W} \\left(\\frac{t_{ij}}{\\Pi_i P_j}\\right)^{1-\\sigma}$. The same functional form arises from different micro-foundations.<br><br>3. Eaton and Kortum (2002) — Ricardian model with many goods: Countries have random productivity draws for each good. Trade costs are iceberg. The model yields a gravity equation: $X_{ij} = \\frac{Y_i Y_j}{Y^W} \\left(\\frac{t_{ij}}{\\Pi_i P_j}\\right)^{-\\theta}$, where θ is the dispersion of productivity (comparative advantage strength).<br><br>Key insight: All three derivations yield the same gravity equation structure, differing only in the interpretation of the trade cost elasticity. The multilateral resistance terms ($\\Pi_i$ and $P_j$) are crucial — they capture the fact that trade between i and j depends not only on bilateral barriers but also on barriers that i and j face with all other countries. Anderson and van Wincoop (2003) showed that omitting multilateral resistance leads to biased estimates.",
