  "summary": "The Gravity Model of Trade is an empirical regularity that predicts bilateral trade flows between two countries based on their economic sizes (GDP) and the distance between them. The basic gravity equation is $T_{ij} = A \\times \\frac{GDP_i \\times GDP_j}{D_{ij}}$, where trade is proportional to the product of GDPs and inversely proportional to distance. The model typically explains 60-80% of the variation in bilateral trade flows, making it one of the most successful empirical regularities in economics. Taking natural logs transforms the equation into a linear regression: $\\ln(T_{ij}) = \\ln(A) + \\ln(GDP_i) + \\ln(GDP_j) - \\ln(D_{ij}) + \\epsilon_{ij}$.<br><br>The gravity model has strong theoretical foundations. Anderson (1979) derived it from the Armington assumption (goods differentiated by country of origin). Helpman and Krugman (1985) derived it from monopolistic competition with increasing returns. Eaton and Kortum (2002) derived it from a Ricardian model with many goods. Anderson and van Wincoop (2003) showed the importance of multilateral resistance terms — trade between i and j depends not only on bilateral barriers but also on barriers that i and j face with all other countries. The structural gravity equation is $X_{ij} = \\frac{Y_i Y_j}{Y^W} \\left(\\frac{t_{ij}}{\\Pi_i P_j}\\right)^{1-\\sigma}$, where $\\Pi_i$ and $P_j$ are multilateral resistance terms.<br><br>Empirical estimates typically find GDP elasticities close to 1 and a distance elasticity between -0.5 and -1.5 (most often around -1). Extended gravity models include additional variables: contiguity (shared border) increases trade by 50-100%; common language increases trade by 50-200%; colonial ties increase trade by 100-300%; trade agreements increase trade by 50-200%. The border effect — the reduction in trade from crossing an international border — is estimated to be 2-5 times (i.e., trade within a country is 2-5 times larger than trade between countries after controlling for GDP and distance).<br><br>The gravity model is widely used for policy analysis. Studies find that the EU increased trade among members by 100-200%; NAFTA increased trade by 50-100%; the WTO increased trade by 20-50%. Gravity models predicted that Brexit would reduce UK-EU trade by 15-50%, and actual post-Brexit data show a decline of about 15%. Currency unions (euro, dollarization) increase trade by 10-20%.<br><br>Modern extensions include: heterogeneous firms (Melitz model) — trade liberalization increases trade through both intensive margin (existing exporters export more) and extensive margin (new firms start exporting). PPML estimation (Santos Silva and Tenreyro, 2006) handles zero trade flows and heteroskedasticity, becoming the standard estimator. Value-added trade measures account for global value chains, showing that value-added trade is less sensitive to distance than gross trade.<br><br>The gravity model is the workhorse of empirical trade analysis, used by international organizations (WTO, World Bank, IMF), governments, and academics to evaluate trade policies, forecast trade flows, and test trade theories. Its strong empirical performance and solid theoretical foundations make it indispensable for understanding international trade patterns and the effects of trade policy changes.",
